inenumber\">3\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]SOLO❦&nbsp;&nbsp;[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cspan class=\"textpartnumber\" id=\"abb\">fragment (physical) b\u003C/span>\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"divb--diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"ab-l1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]...[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cspan class=\"textpartnumber\" id=\"abc\">fragment (physical) c\u003C/span>\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"divc--diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"ac-l1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">··\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"ac-l2-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">·\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>  \u003Cspan>Text based upon drawings in Agnello 1956\u003C/span>  \u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>The largest fragment (a) was published by Orsi in 1923, without reference to the existence of a Greek text on the reverse. The other two fragments were published, together with the first fragment, by Agnello in 1956, but he only provided drawings of each, stating that the fragments did not join and declined to attempt any editing of the text. The fragments appear to offer a typical example of the re-use of an imperial period Latin funerary plaque for a later Greek funerary plaque in the catacombs.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Orsi 1923 no.4 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001699\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001699\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003Cli> Agnello 1956 26 p, fig.7a-c \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002207\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002207\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003Cli> Marchese 2012 no.43 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002550\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002550\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\"> Line 1    Interlineation line 1 to 2    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a Creative Commons-Attribution 4.0 licence. \u003C/div>",[198,201,204,207,210,213,216,219],{"id":199,"html":200},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cspan class=\"textpartnumber\" id=\"aba\">fragment (physical) a\u003C/span>  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"diva--interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"aa-l1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">...\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003Cbr id=\"aa-l2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cspan data-type=\"persname\" data-name-type=\"attested\" data-